# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1872-boston-red-stockings-season
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1872-boston-red-stockings-season/1871-boston-red-stockings-season] The 1871 season was the first season of the Boston Red Stockings franchise, now known as the Atlanta Braves.
[src:1872-boston-red-stockings-season/1871-boston-red-stockings-season] They were formed in 1871 by Boston businessman and Ashburnham native Ivers Whitney Adams.
[src:1872-boston-red-stockings-season/1871-boston-red-stockings-season] The team was composed of former players of the defunct Cincinnati Red Stockings franchise, who were brought to Boston and kept the name with them.
[src:1872-boston-red-stockings-season/1871-boston-red-stockings-season] Led and managed by baseball pioneer Harry Wright, the new Boston team would join the newly formed National Association of Professional Base Ball Players for the 1871 season and finish the year in third place with a record of 20–10.
[src:1872-boston-red-stockings-season/1871-boston-red-stockings-season] Pitcher Al Spalding started all 31 of the Red Stockings' games and led the NA with 19 wins.
[src:1872-boston-red-stockings-season/1871-boston-red-stockings-season] Catcher Cal McVey finished second in the league batting race with a .431 average.
[src:1872-boston-red-stockings-season/1871-boston-red-stockings-season] From this team, Harry Wright, Al Spalding, and shortstop George Wright have all been elected into the Baseball Hall of Fame.
[src:1872-boston-red-stockings-season/1871-major-league-baseball-season] The tenth founding member, the National club of Washington, did not enter a team for the championship until 1872.
[src:1872-boston-red-stockings-season/1871-philadelphia-athletics-season] With the debut of the first professional baseball league, the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players, the Athletic Baseball Club of Philadelphia was one of the first clubs to join.
[src:1872-boston-red-stockings-season/1871-philadelphia-athletics-season] The Athletics had been around since 1860 as an amateur club.
[src:1872-boston-red-stockings-season/1871-philadelphia-athletics-season] Led by their captain and pitcher, Dick McBride, the team went 21–7 and won the first NA title during the 1871 season.
[src:1872-boston-red-stockings-season/1871-philadelphia-athletics-season] Philadelphia's third baseman, Levi Meyerle, led the league with a .492 batting average.
[src:1872-boston-red-stockings-season/1872-baltimore-canaries-season] The Baltimore Canaries played their first season in 1872 as a member of the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players.
[src:1872-boston-red-stockings-season/1872-baltimore-canaries-season] They finished second in the league with a record of 35–19.
[src:1872-boston-red-stockings-season/1872-baltimore-canaries-season] Outfielder Lip Pike led the NA in home runs, with 7, and runs batted in, with 60.
[src:1872-boston-red-stockings-season/1872-baltimore-canaries-season] Pitcher Bobby Mathews paced the circuit in strikeouts.
[src:1872-boston-red-stockings-season/1872-baltimore-canaries-season] Baltimore's other pitcher, Cherokee Fisher, led in earned run average.
[src:1872-boston-red-stockings-season/1872-baltimore-canaries-season] Several of the team's players were later suspended from baseball for fixing games; Bill Craver, George Hall, and Dick Higham were banned for life.
[src:1872-boston-red-stockings-season/1872-boston-red-stockings-season] The **1872 Boston Red Stockings season** was the second season of the franchise.
[src:1872-boston-red-stockings-season/1872-boston-red-stockings-season] They won the National Association championship.
[src:1872-boston-red-stockings-season/1872-boston-red-stockings-season] Managed by Harry Wright, Boston finished with a record of 39–8 to win the pennant by 7.5 games.
[src:1872-boston-red-stockings-season/1872-boston-red-stockings-season] Pitcher Al Spalding started all 48 of the Red Stockings' games and led the NA with 38 wins.
[src:1872-boston-red-stockings-season/1872-boston-red-stockings-season] Second baseman Ross Barnes won the league batting title with a .430 batting average.
[src:1872-boston-red-stockings-season/1872-boston-red-stockings-season] Harry Wright, Al Spalding, and shortstop George Wright have all been elected into the Baseball Hall of Fame.
[src:1872-boston-red-stockings-season/1872-brooklyn-atlantics-season] The Brooklyn Atlantics played their first season of professional baseball in 1872 as a member of the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players, following many successful years as an amateur team.
[src:1872-boston-red-stockings-season/1872-brooklyn-atlantics-season] They finished sixth in the league with a record of 9–28.
[src:1872-boston-red-stockings-season/1872-brooklyn-eckfords-season] The **Brooklyn Eckfords** played their first and only season of professional baseball in 1872 as a member of the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players.
[src:1872-boston-red-stockings-season/1872-brooklyn-eckfords-season] They finished ninth in the league with a record of 3-26.
[src:1872-boston-red-stockings-season/1872-cleveland-forest-citys-season] The **Cleveland Forest Citys** played their second and final season in 1872 as a member of the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players.
[src:1872-boston-red-stockings-season/1872-cleveland-forest-citys-season] They finished seventh in the league with a record of 6–16.
[src:1872-boston-red-stockings-season/1872-cleveland-forest-citys-season] The team folded at the conclusion of the season.
